{"cursor":"29386","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nIn generative linguistics, 'focus' determines which part of the sentence\ncontributes new or non-derivable information. {{Citation\n  | first = M. last = Halliday author = authorlink = coauthors = title = Notes\n  | on Transitivity and Theme in English (Part 2) version = publisher = Journal\n  | of Linguistics 3. year = 1967 url = page = 206 accessdate = }}\nFocus is related to information structure. 'Contrastive focus' specifically\nrefers to the coding of information that is contrary to the presuppositions of\nthe interlocutor.\n\nRelated terms include Comment and Rheme.\n","linknr":352,"url":"Focus_(linguistics)","recorded":1362667596,"links":21,"instances":["linguistics","linguistics","linguistics","linguistics","linguistics","linguistics","linguistics","mathematics"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Syntactic entities","Semantics"],"headings":["Generative approaches","See also","Notes","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/b/bb/SyntaxSplit.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d1/LeftPeriphery_Rizzi_1997_eng.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/8/81/RoothOrdinary.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/f/1/0f1ab8157e3378349df63449f415f06f.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/9/7/297d0767fd2aa3e9414ed8ca11be4821.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/4/8/5488b84330c41943b18247df5b9c1357.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/2/2c/KrifkaFocus.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/9/8/998f78d766ce21eaeead979a2eee65bd.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/7/6/176191246ce7ba0fc8d085ae3a800b67.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/b/3/bb3fb6533d857290cfd02f50fa1094ac.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/3/e/93ebe8636e1f8d60004fe33d1321674e.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/3/e/93ebe8636e1f8d60004fe33d1321674e.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/3/e/93ebe8636e1f8d60004fe33d1321674e.png","//upload.wikimed